Our task¶

In this notebook, we want to find out the possibilities of predicting the equipment failure in a period of future time using historical error information of selected machines. More detailedly, we hope to predict whether the equipment will fail (In the submission, we use 0 for successful operating, 1 for failure) on the following features of the previous days: for each of the 26 types of error messages:

  1. the number of occurences in a day,

  2. the mean of the occurences in a single day, and

  3. the standard deviation of the occurences in a single day.

Our flow¶

Our experiment evolves as the following :

  1. Data Preprocessing,
  2. Preliminary Analysis,
  3. Model Build And Test,
  4. Prediction and Output.

Data Introduction and Preprocessing¶

The dataset is given into 2 parts. One is the test data feature and the other one is training data. Both two sets contain error information given machine ID and time stamp. Each piece of error information is illustrated through 26 features and each feature is composed of 3 figures, count, mean and standard deviation.

Before importing data into Python for further processing, we reformat the data using R. The reason we use R is that it could provide a direct view of data inside and more convenient tools of dealing with Data.Frame data.

Step 1 Revise the tags

After a simple glance at the data, we find that the column tags are given in 2 rows. As we want to adopt Data.Frame as a tool in Python, we combine two tags into one. Then the tags after revision would be "Machine","Date","Error Feature ID + Count","Error Feature ID + Mean", "Error Feature ID + SD". In the training data, there would be another tag called "Label".

Step 2 Reformat the date

Since the date data are given into different formats originally, i.e "yyyy-m-d"/"yyyy-mm-dd",in order to unify the "Date" data, we use the R function "uclass" and "as.Date" to revise them. Then all the dates would be changed into the numbers of days between the base date "1970-01-01" and the original one. This is applied to both two datasets.

Step 3 Clean the useless data

In the data, we find that some error information is given as following: Count = 1, Mean = NaN, SD = NaN. We treat this as useless, because this error is incomplete. Thus we wipe out this kind of information.

The R codes are shown as below:

rm(list=ls())

#Define file paths
feature_path = "/Users/hypnos/Desktop/Nexperia/Original Data/test_feature/"
train_path = "/Users/hypnos/Desktop/Nexperia/Original Data/training_data/"

output_path = "/Users/hypnos/Desktop/Nexperia/Cleaned Data/"

#Define file names 
feature_namelist = c("Verification freq 1D, OW 1, PW 1_feature.csv","Verification freq 1D, OW 2, PW 1_feature.csv","Verification freq 1D, OW 4, PW 1_feature.csv","Verification freq 1D, OW 8, PW 1_feature.csv","Verification freq 1D, OW 16, PW 1_feature.csv")
train_namelist = c("Training freq 1D, OW 1, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 2, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 4, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 8, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 16, PW 1.csv")


for (each in feature_namelist){
  #Read feature data
  feature = read.csv(paste0(feature_path,each,sep="")) 

  #Combine column tags
  for (i in 1:ncol(feature)){ 
    colnames(feature)[i] = paste0(colnames(feature)[i],feature[1,i],sep="")
    colnames(feature)[i] = substr(colnames(feature)[i],2,nchar(colnames(feature)[i]))
  }
  colnames(feature)[2] = "Machine"
  colnames(feature)[3] = "Date"

  #Clean incomplete data
  for (i in 1:nrow(feature)){
    for (j in 1:ncol(feature)){
      if (as.character(feature[i,j]) == "1.0"){
        feature[i,j] = ""
      }
    }
  }

  #Delete useless columns
  feature = as.data.frame(feature)
  feature <- feature[-c(1,2),]
  feature <- feature[,-1]

  #Revise dates
  for (i in feature["Date"]){
    i = unclass(as.Date(i))
  }
  feature["Date"]=as.data.frame(i)

  #File output
  write.csv(feature,file = paste0(output_path,each,sep=""), row.names = FALSE)
}

for (each in train_namelist){
  #Read feature data
  train = read.csv(paste0(train_path,each,sep=""))

  #Combine column tags
  for (i in 1:ncol(train)-1){
    colnames(train)[i] = paste0(colnames(train)[i],train[1,i],sep="")
    colnames(train)[i] = substr(colnames(train)[i],2,nchar(colnames(train)[i]))
  }
  colnames(train)[1] = "Machine"
  colnames(train)[2] = "Date"

  #Clean incomplete data
  for (i in 1:nrow(train)){
    for (j in 1:ncol(train)){
      if (as.character(train[i,j]) == "1.0"){
        train[i,j] = ""
      }
    }
  }

  #Revise dates
  train = as.data.frame(train)
  train <- train[-c(1,2),]
  for (i in train["Date"]){
    i = unclass(as.Date(i))
  }
  train["Date"]=as.data.frame(i)

  #File output
  write.csv(train,file = paste0(output_path,each,sep=""), row.names = FALSE)
}

Observations on Missing Data¶

It appears to show thar there are numerous missing data. However in this project, there's no missing data, where blank cell represents nothing.

Cleansing the Data¶

Since there exists some difference in datatype bwtween training set and testing set. Data cleansing is executed as follows:

In [6]:
print("cleans the data...")

#fill in the null value with the mean value of this column

cleans the data...

There are a lot of missing values in each column according to the previous analysis of the data. So we filled up all n/a with the mean value of this column. If we use all 0 to fill them, there will be a lot of useless data and these columns will not be very representative. And mean value should be a non-zero value. So they can kind of simulate the real data. And provide more evidence to the prediction.

Explore the Linear Relationship between Result and Features (R)¶

Since R language provides a better support on panel data, we first apply linear regression on the training data to verify whether there is a possible linear relationship between the error and some specific features. And here we use "Machine" and "Date" as the indexes.

The R codes are shown as below:

rm(list=ls())
library(plm)

setwd("/Users/hypnos/Desktop/Nexperia/Cleaned Data")
namelist = c("Training freq 1D, OW 1, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 2, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 4, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 8, PW 1.csv","Training freq 1D, OW 16, PW 1.csv")

for (name in namelist){
  data = read.csv(name)
  data[is.na(data)] <- 0
  data = pdata.frame(data, index = c("Machine","Date"))

  plm_test = plm(Label~count.0+vMean.0+vStd.0   
                 +count.1+vMean.1+vStd.1+count.2+vMean.2+vStd.2
                 +count.3+vMean.3+vStd.3+count.4+vMean.4+vStd.4 
                 +count.5+vMean.5+vStd.5+count.6+vMean.6+vStd.6 
                 +count.7+vMean.7+vStd.7+count.8+vMean.8+vStd.8 
                 +count.9+vMean.9+vStd.9+count.10+vMean.10+vStd.10  
                 +count.11+vMean.11+vStd.11+count.12+vMean.12+vStd.12   
                 +count.13+vMean.13+vStd.13+count.14+vMean.14+vStd.14   
                 +count.15+vMean.15+vStd.15+count.16+vMean.16+vStd.16
                 +count.17+vMean.17+vStd.17+count.18+vMean.18+vStd.18   
                 +count.19+vMean.19+vStd.19+count.20+vMean.20+vStd.20   
                 +count.21+vMean.21+vStd.21+count.22+vMean.22+vStd.22   
                 +count.23+vMean.23+vStd.23+count.24+vMean.24+vStd.24   
                 +count.25+vMean.25+vStd.25+count.26+vMean.26+vStd.26, data = data, model = "within")

  summary(plm_test)
}

Although all of the five regression results show that there are significant linear relationships between the running status and the 26 features, the Adj.R values are quite small which indicate that all the models are weak at illustrating the variance. At the same time, we do find some features that are significant in all the cases, which meaning that some of them could be used as inputs for future learning. And linear regression could be taken into account.

from sklearn import linear_model
model = linear_model.LinearRegression()
linear_regression_used = 1
model.fit(train[feature], train["result"])
predict_data = model.predict(test[feature])
print("finish prediction...")
predict_data_train = model.predict(train[feature])
predict_data_train_frame = pd.DataFrame({
        "result": predict_data_train
        })
predict_data_train_frame.loc[predict_data_train_frame['result'] > 0.0773,'result'] = round(1)  
predict_data_train_frame.loc[predict_data_train_frame['result'] <= 0.0773,'result'] = round(0)
print("training accuracy...")
linear_regression_accuracy = accuracy_score(predict_data_train_frame["result"],train["result"])
print(linear_regression_accuracy)
print("training accurate terms count...")
print(accuracy_score(predict_data_train_frame["result"],train["result"],normalize=False))

Conclusion¶

Model evaluation¶

The comparison among training accuracy of different models is shown below:

In [24]:
models = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': ['Decision Tree','XGBoost','Linear Regression','Random Forest','Support Vector Machine','Advanced Support Vector Machine', 'K Clusters','K Nearest Neighbours'],
    'Training accuracy': [decision_tree_accuracy, xgboost_accuracy, linear_regression_accuracy,random_forest_accuracy, support_vector_accuracy, advanced_support_vector_accuracy, k_clusters_accuracy, k_nearest_neighbours_accuracy]})
models.sort_values(by='Training accuracy', ascending=False)
Out[24]:
Model Training accuracy
0 Decision Tree 1.000000
4 Support Vector Machine 1.000000
5 Advanced Support Vector Machine 1.000000
3 Random Forest 0.983118
1 XGBoost 0.925288
7 K Nearest Neighbours 0.925115
6 K Clusters 0.874989
2 Linear Regression 0.642801

As shown above, although many models show high traning accuracy, there're still overfitting.

And one interesting finding is that although Linear Regression has a worst training accuracy on the above list, it has the best performance on the Kaggle contest. All other methods will only attain an accuracy around 0.49~0.51.

Analysis: We may notice that there are several predicting methods can reach 100% accuracy on the training set. That should be good according to our past experience. However, the reason why we don't use these methods is that they are in serious overfitting situations.The number of dimensions is relatively large for this dataset, so it is easier to overfit into the training dataset.

Reason: We may find the reason from the performance of all methods. There is a phenomenon. With a method other than the linear regression model, they will provide a prediction result filled with almost all 0. And for a linear regression model, most of the prediction results are in range of 0 to 0.15.

This means that the True label will be not that obvious to derive from the features. The data together can only provide a weak prediction on the result. They are strong proofs for "False". It is hard for them to get to a state with a high confidence to label it as "True". In order to solve this problem, we may need to adjust the threshold to get more "True" as results.

Finally we come up with a linear regression model with the threshold set to 0.075. This value can provide an accuracy rate of 0.54310.

Above all, we evetually choose the linear regression model to finish and sumit the pridiction.
